performance_optimizations.description:
Parallelize the Q3 lineitem scan and aggregation phase using morsel-driven parallelism. This is the HIGHEST IMPACT optimization.

Current bottleneck: The lineitem scan + probe + aggregation takes 2000ms+ sequentially. With 4 threads, we can achieve near-linear speedup (4x) to ~500-600ms.

Implementation strategy:
1. Keep the customer filtering and orders hash table build phase as-is (these are fast: 30ms + 300ms = 330ms total)

2. Parallelize the lineitem scan phase using morsel-driven execution:
   - Divide lineitem into morsels (chunks) of ~10K-50K rows each
   - Use atomic counter to distribute morsels to threads
   - Each thread maintains its own thread-local revenue_map (RobinHoodMap<Q3GroupKey, double>)
   - Each thread independently scans its morsels, filters by shipdate, probes order_info (read-only, no locks), and aggregates into local map

3. Merge phase: After all threads finish, merge their local revenue_maps into a global result
   - This is serial but fast (<50ms for ~50K groups across 4 threads)

4. Use std::thread or OpenMP for thread management

Code skeleton:
```cpp
#include <thread>
#include <atomic>
#include <vector>

struct Morsel {
    size_t start_idx;
    size_t count;
};

const size_t NUM_THREADS = std::thread::hardware_concurrency(); // 4-8 typical
const size_t MORSEL_SIZE = 50000; // Tune based on profiling

std::atomic<size_t> next_morsel{0};
size_t total_morsels = (lineitem.size() + MORSEL_SIZE - 1) / MORSEL_SIZE;

struct ThreadLocalState {
    alignas(64) RobinHoodMap<Q3GroupKey, double, Q3GroupKeyHash> local_revenue_map;
    ThreadLocalState() : local_revenue_map(10000) {}  // Pre-size
};

std::vector<ThreadLocalState> thread_states(NUM_THREADS);

auto worker = [&](size_t thread_id) {
    auto& local_map = thread_states[thread_id].local_revenue_map;

    while (true) {
        size_t morsel_idx = next_morsel.fetch_add(1, std::memory_order_relaxed);
        if (morsel_idx >= total_morsels) break;

        size_t start = morsel_idx * MORSEL_SIZE;
        size_t end = std::min(start + MORSEL_SIZE, lineitem.size());

        // Process this morsel: filter + probe + aggregate
        for (size_t i = start; i < end; i++) {
            if (l_shipdate[i] > lineitem_min_date) {
                auto* order_data = order_info.find(l_orderkey[i]);  // Read-only probe
                if (order_data != nullptr) {
                    Q3GroupKey key{l_orderkey[i], order_data->first, order_data->second};
                    double revenue = l_extendedprice[i] * (1.0 - l_discount[i]);
                    local_map[key] += revenue;
                }
            }
        }
    }
};

// Launch threads
std::vector<std::thread> threads;
for (size_t i = 0; i < NUM_THREADS; i++) {
    threads.emplace_back(worker, i);
}
for (auto& t : threads) t.join();

// Merge thread-local maps into global result
RobinHoodMap<Q3GroupKey, double, Q3GroupKeyHash> revenue_map(50000);
for (auto& state : thread_states) {
    for (auto it = state.local_revenue_map.begin(); it != state.local_revenue_map.end(); ++it) {
        auto [key, rev] = *it;
        revenue_map[key] += rev;
    }
}
```

Key considerations:
- order_info hash map is read-only during probe phase (no locks needed)
- Thread-local aggregation avoids lock contention
- Use alignas(64) to prevent false sharing between thread-local states
- Morsel size of 50K rows balances load distribution with cache locality
- Zone map filtering can be done per-morsel or globally (recommend per-morsel for simplicity)

Expected improvement: 4-6x speedup on Q3 lineitem processing phase (2000ms -> 330-500ms). Total Q3: 2369ms -> 660-830ms (2.8-3.6x speedup).

Files to modify:
- queries/q3.cpp: Add parallel execution for lineitem scan phase
- May need to add <thread>, <atomic> includes

Risks: Thread synchronization bugs, need to test with different thread counts

Add a bloom filter on the order_info hash table keys to skip ~70-80% of lineitem probes that won't match.

Motivation: After customer filtering (150K -> matching segment) and orders filtering (15M -> 6M by date), we build order_info with ~500K unique orderkeys. During lineitem scan, we probe with ~20M filtered lineitems. However, lineitem has ~4M unique orderkeys total, so many lineitems reference orders that aren't in our filtered set. A bloom filter can quickly reject these non-matching keys without accessing the hash table.

Implementation:
1. After building order_info hash map, construct a bloom filter with all its keys
   - Use ~8 bits per key for <1% false positive rate: 500K keys × 8 bits = 500KB
   - Can use simple bit vector with 2-3 hash functions (MurmurHash3 with different seeds)

2. During lineitem probe, first check bloom filter:
   - If bloom says "definitely not present", skip hash table probe (saves 100-200 cycles)
   - If bloom says "maybe present", do normal hash table probe

3. Simple bloom filter implementation:
```cpp
class BloomFilter {
    std::vector<uint64_t> bits_;  // Use uint64_t for word-aligned access
    size_t num_bits_;

public:
    BloomFilter(size_t expected_elements, double fp_rate = 0.01) {
        // Calculate optimal size: -n*ln(p) / (ln(2)^2)
        num_bits_ = -1.0 * expected_elements * std::log(fp_rate) / (std::log(2) * std::log(2));
        bits_.resize((num_bits_ + 63) / 64, 0);
    }

    void insert(int32_t key) {
        uint64_t h1 = hash1(key);
        uint64_t h2 = hash2(key);
        bits_[(h1 % num_bits_) / 64] |= (1ULL << ((h1 % num_bits_) % 64));
        bits_[(h2 % num_bits_) / 64] |= (1ULL << ((h2 % num_bits_) % 64));
    }

    bool might_contain(int32_t key) const {
        uint64_t h1 = hash1(key);
        uint64_t h2 = hash2(key);
        bool bit1 = bits_[(h1 % num_bits_) / 64] & (1ULL << ((h1 % num_bits_) % 64));
        bool bit2 = bits_[(h2 % num_bits_) / 64] & (1ULL << ((h2 % num_bits_) % 64));
        return bit1 && bit2;
    }

private:
    uint64_t hash1(int32_t key) const { return key * 0x9e3779b97f4a7c15ULL; }  // Simple multiplicative hash
    uint64_t hash2(int32_t key) const { return key * 0xbf58476d1ce4e5b9ULL; }
};

// After building order_info:
BloomFilter order_bloom(order_info.size());
for (auto it = order_info.begin(); it != order_info.end(); ++it) {
    order_bloom.insert(it->first);  // it->first is the orderkey
}

// During lineitem probe:
for (size_t i = start; i < end; i++) {
    if (l_shipdate[i] > lineitem_min_date) {
        int32_t orderkey = l_orderkey[i];

        // Bloom filter pre-check
        if (!order_bloom.might_contain(orderkey)) {
            continue;  // Definitely not in order_info, skip probe
        }

        // Probe hash table (bloom said maybe present)
        auto* order_data = order_info.find(orderkey);
        if (order_data != nullptr) {
            // ... aggregation logic
        }
    }
}
```

Expected improvement: Bloom filter avoids 70-80% of hash table probes for non-matching keys. Since hash probe costs ~100-200 cycles (cache miss + linear probing), bloom check costs ~10-20 cycles (two cache-line accesses), net savings is significant. Estimate 20-30% speedup on lineitem probe phase.

Note: This optimization stacks with parallelization (Priority 1). Each thread can share the same bloom filter (read-only).

Files to modify:
- queries/q3.cpp: Add BloomFilter class or include external bloom filter library
- Add bloom filter construction after order_info build
- Add bloom filter check before hash table probe

Risks: Bloom filter construction cost (~20ms for 500K keys), false positive rate tuning

Parallelize Q1 lineitem scan and aggregation using morsel-driven parallelism, similar to Q3.

Motivation: Q1 processes 59M rows (98% pass shipdate filter) in 249ms. With 4 threads, we can achieve ~3x speedup (accounting for merge overhead) to ~80-100ms, approaching DuckDB's 199ms.

Implementation strategy:
1. Each thread maintains a local direct-indexed aggregation array (std::vector<Q1Aggregates> agg_array(256*256))
2. Threads process morsels independently, updating their local aggregation arrays
3. Merge phase: Sum all thread-local arrays element-wise into global result

Code sketch:
```cpp
const size_t NUM_THREADS = std::thread::hardware_concurrency();
const size_t MORSEL_SIZE = 100000;  // Larger morsel for Q1 (simpler aggregation)

struct ThreadLocalQ1State {
    alignas(64) std::vector<Q1Aggregates> agg_array;
    std::vector<bool> group_exists;

    ThreadLocalQ1State() : agg_array(65536), group_exists(65536, false) {}
};

std::vector<ThreadLocalQ1State> thread_states(NUM_THREADS);
std::atomic<size_t> next_morsel{0};
size_t total_morsels = (n + MORSEL_SIZE - 1) / MORSEL_SIZE;

auto worker = [&](size_t thread_id) {
    auto& local_agg = thread_states[thread_id].agg_array;
    auto& local_exists = thread_states[thread_id].group_exists;

    while (true) {
        size_t morsel_idx = next_morsel.fetch_add(1, std::memory_order_relaxed);
        if (morsel_idx >= total_morsels) break;

        size_t start = morsel_idx * MORSEL_SIZE;
        size_t end = std::min(start + MORSEL_SIZE, n);

        // Zone map filtering can be done here per-morsel
        for (size_t i = start; i < end; i++) {
            if (shipdate[i] <= max_date) {
                size_t idx = (static_cast<size_t>(returnflag_code[i]) << 8) | linestatus_code[i];
                local_exists[idx] = true;

                // ... aggregation logic (same as current)
                local_agg[idx].sum_qty += quantity[i];
                // ... etc
            }
        }
    }
};

// Launch threads
std::vector<std::thread> threads;
for (size_t i = 0; i < NUM_THREADS; i++) {
    threads.emplace_back(worker, i);
}
for (auto& t : threads) t.join();

// Merge: Sum all thread-local aggregation arrays
std::vector<Q1Aggregates> global_agg(65536);
std::vector<bool> global_exists(65536, false);

for (auto& state : thread_states) {
    for (size_t idx = 0; idx < 65536; idx++) {
        if (state.group_exists[idx]) {
            global_exists[idx] = true;
            global_agg[idx].sum_qty += state.agg_array[idx].sum_qty;
            global_agg[idx].sum_base_price += state.agg_array[idx].sum_base_price;
            // ... etc for all 6 aggregates
        }
    }
}
```

Key considerations:
- Merge overhead is minimal: only 4-6 groups are non-empty, so merging 4 threads × 6 groups = 24 entries
- Zone map filtering can be done globally or per-morsel
- Direct-indexed aggregation is embarrassingly parallel (no hash table contention)
- Use larger morsel size (100K) since aggregation is simpler than Q3 joins

Expected improvement: 3-3.5x speedup with 4 threads (249ms -> 70-85ms). May not reach DuckDB's 199ms if they're using more advanced SIMD or prefetching, but significant improvement.

Files to modify:
- queries/q1.cpp: Add parallel execution with thread-local aggregation

Risks: Low - direct-indexed aggregation is very parallel-friendly

Add software prefetching to hide memory latency during hash table lookups in Q3.

Motivation: Hash table probes incur 100-200 cycle latency due to cache misses. By prefetching the hash bucket we'll need 8-16 iterations in the future, we can overlap memory access with computation.

Implementation:
```cpp
const size_t PREFETCH_DISTANCE = 8;  // Tune based on profiling

for (size_t i = start; i < end; i++) {
    if (l_shipdate[i] > lineitem_min_date) {
        // Prefetch future lookup
        if (i + PREFETCH_DISTANCE < end && l_shipdate[i + PREFETCH_DISTANCE] > lineitem_min_date) {
            int32_t future_key = l_orderkey[i + PREFETCH_DISTANCE];

            // Prefetch bloom filter bits (if using bloom filter)
            if (!order_bloom.might_contain(future_key)) {
                // Prefetch the bloom filter check result for future iteration
            }

            // Prefetch hash table bucket
            // This requires exposing bucket address from RobinHoodMap
            // Can add a method: const void* get_bucket_ptr(int32_t key) const
            const void* bucket = order_info.prefetch_bucket(future_key);
            __builtin_prefetch(bucket, 0, 3);  // Read prefetch, high locality
        }

        // Current iteration (data prefetched 8 iterations ago)
        if (!order_bloom.might_contain(l_orderkey[i])) continue;
        auto* order_data = order_info.find(l_orderkey[i]);
        // ... rest of logic
    }
}
```

Note: This requires modifying RobinHoodMap to expose bucket addresses for prefetching. If the custom Robin Hood implementation doesn't support this, this optimization can be skipped.

Expected improvement: 10-15% speedup on hash probe phase. Since probes dominate Q3, this translates to ~100-200ms improvement.

Files to modify:
- utils/robin_hood_map.h: Add prefetch_bucket() method
- queries/q3.cpp: Add prefetching in lineitem probe loop

Risks: Medium - prefetching wrong addresses can hurt performance, need to tune PREFETCH_DISTANCE

Use AVX2 SIMD to vectorize the arithmetic operations in Q1 (disc_factor, disc_price, charge computation).

Motivation: Q1 computes 4 arithmetic expressions per row: disc_factor = 1.0 - discount, disc_price = price * disc_factor, charge = disc_price * (1.0 + tax). These can be vectorized to process 4 doubles at once with AVX2.

Challenges:
- Direct-indexed aggregation makes vectorization complex: each of the 4 processed rows may go to different aggregation slots
- Scatter operations (writing to 4 different agg_array indices) are expensive
- Compiler auto-vectorization struggles with this pattern

Recommended approach: Vectorize only the arithmetic, keep aggregation scalar
```cpp
#ifdef __AVX2__
__m256d one_vec = _mm256_set1_pd(1.0);

for (size_t i = start; i < end - 3; i += 4) {
    // Check if all 4 rows pass date filter (avoid partial SIMD)
    bool all_pass = (shipdate[i] <= max_date) &&
                    (shipdate[i+1] <= max_date) &&
                    (shipdate[i+2] <= max_date) &&
                    (shipdate[i+3] <= max_date);

    if (all_pass) {
        // Vectorized loads
        __m256d price_vec = _mm256_loadu_pd(&price[i]);
        __m256d disc_vec = _mm256_loadu_pd(&discount[i]);
        __m256d tax_vec = _mm256_loadu_pd(&tax[i]);
        __m256d qty_vec = _mm256_loadu_pd(&quantity[i]);

        // Vectorized arithmetic
        __m256d disc_factor = _mm256_sub_pd(one_vec, disc_vec);
        __m256d disc_price = _mm256_mul_pd(price_vec, disc_factor);
        __m256d tax_factor = _mm256_add_pd(one_vec, tax_vec);
        __m256d charge = _mm256_mul_pd(disc_price, tax_factor);

        // Store results and do scalar aggregation
        double disc_factor_arr[4], disc_price_arr[4], charge_arr[4], qty_arr[4];
        _mm256_storeu_pd(disc_factor_arr, disc_factor);
        _mm256_storeu_pd(disc_price_arr, disc_price);
        _mm256_storeu_pd(charge_arr, charge);
        _mm256_storeu_pd(qty_arr, qty_vec);

        // Scalar aggregation (4 iterations)
        for (int j = 0; j < 4; j++) {
            size_t idx = (static_cast<size_t>(returnflag_code[i+j]) << 8) | linestatus_code[i+j];
            group_exists[idx] = true;
            agg_array[idx].sum_qty += qty_arr[j];
            agg_array[idx].sum_base_price += price[i+j];
            agg_array[idx].sum_disc_price += disc_price_arr[j];
            agg_array[idx].sum_charge += charge_arr[j];
            agg_array[idx].sum_discount += discount[i+j];
            agg_array[idx].count++;
        }
    } else {
        // Scalar fallback for rows that don't all pass filter
        // ... (current scalar code)
    }
}
#endif
```

Expected improvement: 20-30% speedup on Q1 arithmetic. However, aggregation scatter overhead may limit gains to 10-15% overall.

Note: This optimization is lower priority than parallelization (Priority 3) which gives 3x speedup. If Priority 3 is implemented, this optimization becomes less valuable.

Files to modify:
- queries/q1.cpp: Add AVX2 SIMD for arithmetic operations

Risks: High - complex to implement correctly, may not provide significant gains due to scatter overhead

Replace std::partial_sort with custom min-heap maintained during aggregation to avoid materializing all groups.

Motivation: Current implementation aggregates all ~50K groups into revenue_map, then uses std::partial_sort to get top 10. With heap-based selection, we can maintain only top 10 groups during aggregation.

Implementation:
```cpp
#include <queue>

struct HeapEntry {
    Q3GroupKey key;
    double revenue;

    bool operator<(const HeapEntry& other) const {
        // Min-heap: smaller revenue at top
        if (revenue != other.revenue) return revenue > other.revenue;
        return key.orderdate > other.orderdate;
    }
};

std::priority_queue<HeapEntry> min_heap;  // Size limited to 10

// During aggregation merge or after aggregation:
for (auto it = revenue_map.begin(); it != revenue_map.end(); ++it) {
    auto [key, rev] = *it;

    if (min_heap.size() < 10) {
        min_heap.push({key, rev});
    } else if (rev > min_heap.top().revenue) {
        min_heap.pop();
        min_heap.push({key, rev});
    }
}
```

Expected improvement: Minimal (<5ms). std::partial_sort is already very efficient for k=10 (O(n log k) where k=10, n=50K). Heap-based selection saves memory but not significant time.

Note: This optimization is very low priority since partial_sort overhead is <2% of Q3 execution time.

Files to modify:
- queries/q3.cpp: Replace partial_sort with heap-based selection

Risks: Low
